                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d863">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1161 Johnston, Eric/1: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-25T23:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 25, 1944—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 26—1:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1044. Have learned from press that Eric Johnston<note n="43" xml:id="d863fn1"
                        >Eric A. Johnston, President of the United States Chamber of
                        Commerce.</note> is planning to come to Russia middle of May. Would
                    appreciate advice on the details of the purposes of his trip and the
                    Department’s views. I welcome his trip and believe his objective should be to
                    obtain information <pb facs="0966" n="956" xml:id="pg_956"/> and create
                    goodwill. I hope Mr. Johnston will be asked to discuss postwar trade matters
                    only in the most general way and after consultation with me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
